JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 124
IS  - 1
SP  - 149
EP  - 195
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Management know-how shapes the productivity of firms and can be reallocated across countries as managers acquire control of factors of production abroad. We construct a quantitative model to investigate the aggregate consequences of the international reallocation of management know-how. Using aggregate data, we infer the relative scarcity of this form of know-how in a sample of developing countries. We find that developing countries gain, on average, 12% in output and 5% in welfare (with wide variation across countries) when they eliminate policy barriers to foreign control of domestic factors of production.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.2009.124.1.149
ER  - 



